This information is used by the Master during generation.

---

# Trap Slots

Rooms never contain predefined traps.

Instead, rooms contain Trap Slots.

Example

TrapSlot_A

TrapSlot_B

TrapSlot_C

A Trap Slot only defines:

- Position
- Direction
- Allowed trap types

Example

TrapSlot_A

Allowed

✓ Arrow Trap

✓ Spike Trap

✓ Pendulum

✗ Boulder

The Master chooses which trap to place.

Or chooses to leave the slot empty.

---

# Modular Corridors

Corridors are independent modules.

Examples

Straight

Corner

Bridge

Stairs

Large Hallway

Collapsed Hallway

The Master connects rooms using corridor modules.

---

# Difficulty Curve

The Labyrinth should tell a story.

Difficulty is not random.

Every run follows a progression.

Example

Learning

↓

Observation

↓

Pressure

↓

Recovery

↓

Challenge

↓

Final Trial

The Master builds the Labyrinth around this curve.

---

# Fairness

The Master follows strict rules.

Never create unavoidable deaths.

Never place impossible trap combinations.

Never block every escape route.

Never require previous knowledge.

Every failure should teach something.

---

# Replayability

Players should recognize environments.

Players should never memorize the entire route.

Knowledge should improve decision making.

Never solve the Labyrinth.

---

# Future Expansion

The architecture allows future additions without changing the generation system.

Possible future features

- New room themes
- New Masters
- Seasonal rooms
- Dynamic events
- Boss rooms
- Environmental hazards
- Multiplayer challenges

Everything integrates into the existing generation pipeline.

---

# Design Goal

Every run should feel handcrafted.

Every run should feel different.

The player should remember stories.

Not layouts.
